# GroceryMate QA Testing Project

## Overview
This project focuses on testing the GroceryMate web application as part of a structured QA process.

The goal was to validate core user flows, identify defects, and ensure a reliable and user-friendly shopping experience.

---

## Application Under Test
GroceryMate (Test Environment)  
https://grocerymate.masterschool.com/

---

## Testing Scope

The testing focused on key user journeys:

- User authentication (login)
- Product browsing and selection
- Add to cart functionality
- Checkout process
- Product rating system
- Age-restricted product flow (e.g. alcohol verification)

---

## Test Approach

### 1. Test Planning
- Defined scope and objectives
- Identified critical user flows
- Prioritized high-impact features

### 2. Test Design
Test cases were created using standard QA techniques:
- Equivalence Partitioning
- Boundary Value Analysis (BVA)
- Use Case Testing

---

## Test Execution

Test cases were executed manually and documented using structured reporting.

Each test includes:
- Steps to reproduce
- Expected vs actual results
- Status (Pass/Fail)
- Linked defects where applicable

---

## Defect Reporting

Bugs were reported using GitHub Issues with the following structure:

- Title and priority
- Environment details
- Steps to reproduce
- Expected result
- Actual result
- Attachments (if available)

Example:
- Dynamic shipping cost not updating in cart
- Rating submission blocked when feedback is empty
- Input validation inconsistencies

---

## Key Findings

- Some UI flows lacked proper validation
- Edge cases (e.g. empty inputs, invalid data) were not consistently handled
- Minor usability issues impacting user experience
- Business logic inconsistencies in checkout flow

---

## Test Coverage

- Functional testing
- Edge case validation
- Input validation testing
- Basic usability testing

---

## Tools Used

- Manual testing
- GitHub (bug tracking)
- PyCharm (test documentation)
- Markdown (reporting)

---

## Repository Contents

- Test cases (Markdown format)
- Bug reports (GitHub Issues)
- Test execution results

---

## Conclusion

This project demonstrates a structured QA approach to validating a real-world web application.  

It highlights the importance of:
- Testing critical user journeys
- Identifying edge cases
- Ensuring product reliability and usability

---

## Notes

All testing was performed in a test environment for learning and demonstration purposes.
